import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

class OrderedStream {
    private String[] stream;
    private int ptr; // Keeps track of the current smallest unreturned index
    public OrderedStream(int n) {
        // Size n + 1 so we can use 1-based idKey indexing safely
        stream = new String[n + 1]; 
        ptr = 1; // The stream expects idKey 1 first
    }
    public List<String> insert(int idKey, String value) {
        List<String> res = new ArrayList<>();
        
        // Insert the value at its 1-based index position
        stream[idKey] = value;
        
        // If the inserted item matches our current expected pointer,
        // collect it and any consecutive items that follow
        while (ptr < stream.length && stream[ptr] != null) {
            res.add(stream[ptr]);
            ptr++; // Move the pointer forward
        }
        
        return res;
    }
}


1. Time Complexity (TC)
OrderedStream(int n): O(n)
Initializing a fixed-size array of size n + 1 takes linear time in Java, as the system allocates memory and fills 
the slots with null.
insert(int idKey, String value): Amortized O(1)
Individual Call: In the worst-case scenario, a single call to insert might run a loop that iterates up to n times 
(e.g., if you insert items 2, 3, 4, 5 out of order, and then finally insert item 1, the pointer will catch up and 
loop through all of them at once). Across all calls: Because the pointer ptr only moves forward and never resets, 
it will visit each index in the array exactly once across the entire lifecycle of the stream. Therefore, over n 
total insertions, the loop runs a maximum of n times total. This averages out to an amortized time complexity of 
O(1) per insertion.

2. Space Complexity (SC)
Overall Class Space: O(n)
We allocate a String[] array of size n + 1 to store the incoming stream elements, which scales linearly with the 
input size n.
insert Method Auxiliary Space: O(1) (excluding the return list)
The method only uses a couple of temporary variables to process the logic. The List<String> res that is returned 
takes up space proportional to the number of elements outputted in that specific call (at most O(n) if all elements 
are released at once), but this is generally considered output space rather than extra auxiliary overhead.

